shared_text:
Brainerd ECFE
Yesterday at 5:28 AM ·

Our preschoolers are excited to start school next week! Families were able to come and meet their teachers and see the classrooms this week, and we were so happy to see all the excited preschoolers! We can’t wait for next week! We still have some preschool openings available so give us a call.

We are also preparing for the start of ECFE and will be giving you sneak peeks right here on our FB page so be watching for that soon!

Thanks for everyone’s support and patience as we prepare for a unique and awesome school year. #bealittlewarrior

shared_text:
National September 11 Memorial & Museum was live.
Yesterday at 7:30 AM ·

On this sacred day, we honor the innocent lives lost and recognize the courage of those who made the ultimate sacrifice and risked their lives to save others 19 years ago. Today, at the 9/11 Memorial, we will hear the names of the 2,983 men, women and children killed as a result of the terrorist events of September 11, 2001 and February 26, 1993. We will stand in solidarity with their families and loved ones as we honor the life of every victim and fulfill our sacred promise to remember always. www.911memorial.org/anniversary

shared_text:
Brainerd Public Schools Archives
July 22 at 11:43 AM ·

Celebration of the coaching career and retirement of Brainerd Public Schools head football coach and former activities director Ron Stolski, scheduled for September 19, 2020, at Cragun’s Legacy, Brainerd, has been postponed indefinitely because of present public health concerns.

Stolski, a graduate of Macalester College, resigned as head coach of the Brainerd Warrior football team in January after 44 seasons in Brainerd and another 14 seasons at Kensington, Clayton, Princeton and Park Center. He remains the executive director of the Minnesota Football Coaches Association.

After January 1, the committee organizing the event will review all relevant factors concerning the event and make appropriate announcements at that time.

shared_text:
Minnesota Department of Human Services
June 30 at 11:21 AM ·

The deadline to apply for pandemic food benefits (P-EBT) has been extended to July 31. DHS and the Minnesota Department of Education urge families with school children – now including those in a school district pre-K program – who received free and reduced-price meals to apply online at www.mn.p-ebt.org. Up to 150,000 eligible families have not yet applied.

P-EBT benefits are issued in a lump sum of $325 per child. Also, an additional $100 per child will be issued in August to all families eligible for P-EBT. More information is in a news release:
http://mn.gov/dhs/media/news/index.jsp?id=1053-438572

post_text: #Blueprint181
shared_text:
Brainerd Public Schools Archives
June 30 at 7:34 PM ·

"Human history becomes more and more a race between education and catastrophe."

H.G. Wells, The Outline of History (1920)

In this third and last suite of photographs made on June 21, 2020 are dominant images depicting extensive construction throughout the building complex known to over 50 BHS graduating classes, a total of perhaps 20,000 students.

The previously untouched inner courtyard is now opened to building activity on all sides by a very wide "gateway" from the south and the removal of interior walls exposing the former courtyard through the soon to be radically different main entrance off South Fifth Street.

Exterior perspectives of the new performing arts center, firmly joined to BHS to facilitate "inside" movement of students to performance areas for the first time in more than 50 years, also is developing its signature presence along South Fifth Street.

And to the west of the PAC, exterior walls are in place for the extensive addition of two stories of classrooms into the former "north parking lot" of BHS.

Brainerd Public Schools Archives
June 3 at 11:39 AM ·

BRAINERD PUBLIC SCHOOLS NOW HAS CONSTRUCTION ACTIVITY AT BRAINERD HIGH SCHOOL, THE NEW PERFORMING ARTS CENTER, NISSWA ELEMENTARY, THE NEW BAXTER ELEMENTARY, THE FORMER BAXTER ELEMENTARY, GARFIELD ELEMENTARY, LOWELL ELEMENTARY, HARRISON ELEMENTARY AND RIVERSIDE ELEMENTARY.

Approval for these forward looking educational investments came from the voters of Independent School District 181, which is approaching its 150th year of delivering educational services to children in central Minnesota.

Photographed here, on May 28, 2020, are select exteriors of BHS and of the PAC, as well as iconic images of Brainerd, as seen from the front of BHS (Brainerd's historic water tower), and of BHS, framed by a tree in the approach to the front door of BHS (an area under construction as the former outdoor commons in the center of North Campus is transitioning into educational spaces consuming most of the commons, a major entry point being the South Fifth Street front door entrance).

"Education is the best provision for old age."

Aristotle (c. 400 B.C.)

Brainerd Public Schools Archives
May 28 at 2:29 PM ·

LATE IN THE MORNING OF MAY 28, THE SECOND OF THREE ELEMENTARY SCHOOL MAJOR CONSTRUCTION PROJECTS WITHIN BRAINERD PUBLIC SCHOOLS, LOWELL ELEMENTARY SCHOOL, BROKE GROUND IN NORTHEAST BRAINERD.

80 years ago, Lowell Elementary held a dedicatory opening as a new elementary school within BPS and today it celebrated the beginning of its "second life" with a ceremony conducted on its front lawn. Leading community speakers addressed the socially distanced and masked small gathering, all adults - including the Superintendent of Schools, Laine Larson, the CEO of the Brainerd Lakes Area Chamber of Commerce, the mayor of the City of Brainerd, the chair of the Board of Education and the principal of Lowell Elementary - but the true keynote speaker was Max Bussler, a Lowell student pictured here, who spoke from the heart and while standing on an overturned milk carton case, without notes.

post_text: John Erickson, Brainerd Public Schools archivist, will appear on “Staying Human,” on Northern Community Radio, KAXE 89.9, Brainer on Sunday, May 24, between 5 and 6 pm. Erickson will tell the story of the 194th Tank Battalion. Each of the young men highlighted in the story attended Brainerd Public Schools during the 1930s and walked the halls of what is now the Washington Educational Services Building.
shared_text:
Brainerd Public Schools Archives
May 17 at 5:01 PM ·

“On a bitterly cold February 1941 night, Company A, 194thTank Battalion marched from Brainerd’s National Guard Armory to the Northern Pacific Railroad depot along streets lined with people to see the 61 men off to training in Washington State.”

And so begins the story, to be told on “Staying Human,” a program of words and music for the spirit and for courage, on Northern Community Radio, KAXE 89.9, Brainerd, and also streamed at www.kaxe.org, on Sunday, May 24, between 5 and 6 pm. John Erickson, Brainerd Public Schools archivist, is the writer and narrator.

“And Then There Was One” focuses on four young men from Company A who fought in the first tank battles of WWII and what then happened to them after they and thousands of others were ordered by their command to surrender to the Imperial Japanese Army in the Philippine Islands.

John Erickson, Brainerd Public Schools archivist, will appear on “Staying Human,” on Northern Community Radio, KAXE 89.9, Brainer on Sunday, May 24, between 5 and 6 pm. Erickson will tell the story of the 194th Tank Battalion. Each of the young men highlighted in the story attended Brainerd Public Schools during the 1930s and walked the halls of what is now the Washington Educational Services Building.

Brainerd Public Schools Archives
May 17 at 5:01 PM ·

“On a bitterly cold February 1941 night, Company A, 194thTank Battalion marched from Brainerd’s National Guard Armory to the Northern Pacific Railroad depot along streets lined with people to see the 61 men off to training in Washington State.”

And so begins the story, to be told on “Staying Human,” a program of words and music for the spirit and for courage, on Northern Community Radio, KAXE 89.9, Brainerd, and also streamed at www.kaxe.org, on Sunday, May 24, between 5 and 6 pm. John Erickson, Brainerd Public Schools archivist, is the writer and narrator.

“And Then There Was One” focuses on four young men from Company A who fought in the first tank battles of WWII and what then happened to them after they and thousands of others were ordered by their command to surrender to the Imperial Japanese Army in the Philippine Islands.

post_text: Senior Spotlight #Classof2020
shared_text:
Brainerd High School
May 13 at 3:42 PM ·

NAME: Trey Pike

FAVORITE SCHOOL MEMORY: One of my fondest school memories was going to Preservation Hall during our band tour to New Orleans. It was an amazing experience, and I am very lucky to have been given that opportunity.

ADVICE FOR YOUNGER STUDENTS: High School is easy, and only gets easier as you go on. You don't need to go to college to get a good job. It's cheaper to learn a trade, such as plumbing, and go from there. Many trades are in high demand because nobody wants to do them. If you do plan on going to college, you don't need to have a plan right away. Plans make it easier, but often fall apart. Go to CLC for your first 2 years. It's a great school to start off at, and also allows you to stay at home for your first years of college.

FUTURE PLANS: I'm going to CLC to get my AA, and then to a 4 year to get a bachelor's in business.

shared_text:

April 20 at 1:12 PM ·

Brainerd Public Schools Food Service is still providing daily meals! We have 3 grab n go sites and offer delivery. Week day meals consist of a sub or PB&J sandwich, fruit, vegetable, milk and treat! shared_text:
Brainerd Public Schools added 27 new photos — at Forestview Middle.
April 10 at 8:56 AM · Baxter, MN ·

"Mandy Gill of Bismarck, ND created a Facebook site for communities to show solidarity and support during quarantine by asking people around the world to place hearts somewhere in or outside of their homes using whatever materials they had. They started with being introduced to Pop artist, Jim Dine, and his art using the symbol of the heart. From there, they were to create something using the heart motif for others to see and communicate the message of love and hope during this time. This was our first distance learning assignment. I hope you enjoy what the Forestview Middle School 8C art kids did to contribute and what they had to say about it." -Kara Hall #aworldofhearts

At this time of uncertainty for all, but especially the Class of 2020 which is missing out on so many final high school memories the Brainerd Warrior Cheerleading team felt that a little extra SPIRIT was needed in our community for these students. They are heading this project with the help from SIGNspot to offer families and community members the opportunity to purchase a sign to place in their yards to show their support and Warrior Pride! This is not a fundraiser, just an opportunity to support and congratulate the Class of 2020.
Orders will be taken through May 1st, 2020. You can order using the Paper Form or Google Form.

post_text: Thank you to everyone that helped make this happen- Brainerd Public Schools Foundation, Essentia Health Brainerd, GLS Promotions LLC and FedEx!!
shared_text:
Brainerd Public Schools Foundation is with Dawn Meierding and Jessica 'Gray' Gangl.
March 27 at 8:42 AM ·

Brainerd Public Schools’ District Technology team reached out to BPSF on Monday asking if we could help them find much needed bags for K-4 device distribution on Wed/Fri. I am so proud to say, together, WE MADE IT HAPPEN!! Thank you Essentia Health Brainerd for for jumping in to partner with the first 1,000 bags and GLS Promotions LLC (Dawn Meierding) for getting these sweet BPSF bags ordered so quickly! Finally, thank you to our local FedEx (Paul Borchert) for intercepting the boxes and making an unscheduled EARLY MORNING delivery to make this all come together in time. 💙 #wearewarriors #smalltownfeels #bettertogether

Thank you Essentia Health Brainerd for for jumping in to partner with the first 1,000 bags and GLS Promotions LLC (Dawn Meierding) for getting these sweet BPSF bags ordered so quickly! BPSF OFFERS OVER 100 DIFFERENT SCHOLARSHIPS - WE HAVE SOMETHING FOR EVERY STUDENT TYPE! The Brainerd Public Schools Foundation is proud to announce the 2020 general application is STILL open for BHS students! Since 1987 the Brainerd Public Schools Foundation has been a vehicle for scholarship dollars for the students of the Brainerd Public Schools - with an estimated value of $117k in awards available this year! CLICK HERE TO APPLY FOR A BPSF SCHOLARSHIP: https://bpsf.academicworks.com/

The application cycle will close on March 1, 2020. Students will NOT be able to modify their application once the cycle is closed. We recommend having a parent or trusted adult proof read their application before the deadline.

The nominee must, during and following his or her career, have exemplified the pride and spirit that is Brainerd Warriors athletics. Nominate as many as you wish in any of three categories:
1.) Player: Must be a Brainerd graduate and out of high school at least seven years.
2.) Coach: Must have coached in District 181.
3.) At Large: Any member of the community who has made significant contributions to BHS athletics.

Induction will be on Monday, April 27, 2020 at the 45th annual All-Sports Banquet.

Send a typed or written resume of the candidate, including present address, phone number, years of service and accomplishments. Please enclose your name and address.

Mail nominations to: Hall of Fame Selection Committee ℅ Charlie Campbell Brainerd High School 702 S. 5th St. Brainerd, MN 56401 Or email: charles.campbell@isd181.org
